post_text:
Kingsland Elementary School is seeking a long-term substitute teacher for Elementary STEAM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Art, Math) beginning October 12, 2020 through December 23, 2020. Candidates should hold or be eligible for a Minnesota teaching license in either Elementary Education or Art Education.

The successful candidate will provide STEM instruction to students in grades K-6 using the Project Lead the Way (PLTW) Launch program, as well as integrating art instruction into program curriculum. PLTW Launch engages elementary students in hands-on activities in computer science, engineering, and biomedical science to encourage collaborative problem solving and design mindsets necessary for 21st century careers.

Please apply online at www.kingsland.k12.mn.us > District > Employment.
Questions about the position may be directed to:

Scott Klavetter, Elementary Principal
Kingsland Public Schools
Spring Valley, Minnesota
(507) 346-7276 ext. 1010
klavetter.scott@kingsland2137.org

AN EQUAL OPPORTUNITY EMPLOYER

post_text:
Parents/Guardians,

As you may be aware, Governor Walz is announcing a decision this Thursday, July 30, 2020, on what Minnesota public schools can do this fall. Districts across the state were tasked with developing three (3) plans.

The three (3) plans, or scenarios, include the following:

1. In-person school resumes (Regular school with everyone).
2. Hybrid (Combination of in-person school and distance learning).
3. Distance learning (no in-person school).

Kingsland has been developing plans for the last month. We will notify parents during the week of August 3-7, 2020 as to what our general plan is based upon the announcement. Nothing will be sent out prior to next week as our staff must read through any guidance put forth by the State.

Please be patient as we tread new waters. Announcements regarding athletics will more than likely be coming shortly afterwards from the Minnesota State High School League (MSHSL).

Jim Hecimovich

Jim

Kingsland Community Education
March 25 at 10:09 PM ·

Hello Preschool Parents,

I am writing to let you know that K-12 schools will be going into a period of Distance Learning from Monday, March 30th through May 4th. Preschools participation in Distance Learning is not required by the Governor's Order, but our Preschool Teachers have been working hard on putting together packets for your children to work on during this time. When these packets are ready to be picked up your child's teacher will contact you.

We will not be charging for April's monthly tuition payment. Thank you to those of you that have already made your April preschool payments and we will automatically apply them to your May tuition payment.

Thank you,
Becky Bicknese
Community Education Director

post_text:
The governor made the announcement yesterday that all Minnesota schools will be closing from Wednesday, March 18 through Friday, March 27, 2020. The announcement was not surprising. Here are a few key items for your information:

1. The eight (8) days of school closure (March 18-27, 2020) will be used for the teaching staff to plan and prepare for the deployment of distance learning. There will be no Elearning/Distance Learning during the eight (8) days.

2. School-Age Child Care (SACC) will operate as normal.

3. A letter will be distributed to parents this afternoon regarding school provided meals during the closure.

4. There will be no MSHSL activities and athletics at any member school. This includes all participation including, but not limited to training, practices, scrimmages, and contests. The previous MSHSL directive prohibiting scrimmages, contests and competitions with other MSHSL programs for Spring activities and athletics will continue until April 6, 2020.

Schools continue to receive updates from the State of Minnesota.

Dear Students and Parents/Guardians,

Thank you for taking the time to help improve our Career and Technical Programming at your school!

Career and Technical Education is a term applied to schools, institutions, and educational programs that specialize in the skilled trades, applied sciences, modern technologies, and career preparation i.e. Industrial Technology(shop classes), Business, Family and Consumer Science, and Agriculture. Below is a link to a survey for Career and Technical Education (CTE) programming. We are using this information to determine our local needs when developing and funding CTE programs within our region. Please take a few minutes to provide some information about the CTE courses offered at your district.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/CLNAS

Thank you,
RIverland Perkins Consortium

19-20 Kingsland High School yearbooks are now available for purchase. The DEADLINE for purchasing is JULY, 1, 2020. Please be sure to get your order in as we will only have a couple of extra available. They will once again at the school in the Fall.

Here is the link to purchase the 19-20 yearbook: https://www.shop.memorybook.com/189811kingslandhighschool/

Once there, you might need to enter the code 189811. Double check that it says Kingsland High School at the top. It will ask for a teacher's name, you can just put your favorites teacher's name there, but please be sure to choose your correct grade for the 19-20 school year in the drop down. Yearbooks start at $45 each.

Also, there is a feature that you may design personal pages with pre-designed templates that only you will receive. They will be shipped directly to you. You may add 4 pages and up to 17 photos. They have an adhesive strip that you may add it into your yearbook, too.

Hey Knights!

Red Ribbon Week is begins when we come back to school on Tuesday October 22!

Red Ribbon Week is a national campaign to make schools drug free. Kingsland combines this week with some direct bullying prevention educators!

Flyers went home in “Friday” folders last Wednesday before break!

JOIN US IN DRESS UP DAYS!

Tuesday - Tie Dye—- be unique be you!
Wednesday - Red —— drug awareness
Thursday - Blue —— bullying prevention
Friday - Black Out —- turn the lights out on drugs and bullying!

Please call Ms. Annie if you have any questions.

Do your best and make good choices knights!

Come on out and support out Kingsland HOSA Chapter on Monday night at the Pizza Place.

HOSA is an international student organization recognized by the U.S. Department of Education and the Health Science Education (HSE) Division of ACTE. HOSA's two-fold mission is to promote career opportunities in the health care industry and to enhance the delivery of quality health care to all people. HOSA's goal is to encourage all health science instructors and students to join and be actively involved in the HSE-HOSA Partnership.

School is starting on time!

Kingsland Public Schools will start on time, Tuesday, September 3, 2019. The project, other than some minor finish-ups, is completed. Please ignore any unfounded rumors contrary to the information just shared with you.

post_text:
Operating Referendum Levy 2019 - Ag Days Parade

Following the Ag Days Parade, members of the Kingsland School Board and Administration will be hosting an Operating Referendum Levy Information Center at the SV Fire Hall from 2:00-4:00 PM. The public can get information, ask questions and see the tax impact on their property.

For more information on the Operating Referendum Levy, please visit:

https://www.kingsland2019.com/

post_text:
High School Open House - Wednesday, August 28, 2019

Kingsland High School is hosting its open house on Wednesday, August 28, 2019 from 4:00 to 7:30 PM. Parents and students can find their classrooms, meet the teachers and get their laptops issued. In addition, two orientation sessions are held in the gymnasium. They are:

Grade 7 Orientation: 6:00 PM
Grade 9 Orientation: 6:30 PM

The open house will allow parents and students to view the recent renovations and upgrades to the building. Please join us on Wednesday, August 28. Outside of the scheduled orientations, the evening is unscheduled. Drop on in!

post_text: If you have ever thought about running for school board now is the perfect time. We are accepting candidate applications for one more week to run for school board member for a one-year term. Forms are available in the District Office and require a $2 filing fee. Election will be held Nov. 5.
